(G) In circumstances in which a local education agency has issued a blanket
consent request to a parent authorizing the entity to make a video or voice recording of
the parent's child on school property during regular instructional hours or extracurricular
activities pursuant to subdivision (c)(12); provided, however, that parental consent must
be obtained before any video or voice recording of the child is published. School
officials are not required to obtain parental consent before the video or voice recording is
initiated.
SECTION 4. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 63-1-176(c), is amended by adding
the following new subdivisions:
(7) A person acts reasonably to render appropriate, non-emergency first aid to a
minor appearing or represented to be sick or injured. Such non-emergency first aid
includes, but is not limited to, dressing minor wounds, applying topical agents, providing
fluids or ice, and performing checks to identify minor illnesses; or
(8) A healthcare provider providing a screening to a minor when they reasonably
believe the minor may be a victim of human trafficking, exploitation, neglect, or abuse.
SECTION 5. This act takes effect July 1, 2025, the public welfare requiring it.
